The '''Lowry Tapes''' refers to a 2013 scandal in Ireland involving the [[Tipperary North (Dáil constituency)|Tipperary North]] [[Teachta Dála|TD]] [[Michael Lowry]], formerly a [[Fine Gael]] government minister. They feature a telephone conversation between Lowry and the land agent Kevin Phelan. The conversation featured foul language and reference to an undeclared payment of €250,000. It is believed to date from 30 September 2004 and raised uncertainty over whether Lowry had misled the [[Moriarty Tribunal]] which had previously investigated him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tv3.ie/article.php?article_id=98152 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130702082643/http://www.tv3.ie/article.php?article_id=98152 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2 July 2013 |title=Lowry tape broadcast |work=TV3 News |date=15 March 2013 |accessdate=15 March 2013 }}</ref>
Much of the controversy focused on the following comments by Lowry:<ref name=journal_conversation_aired_on_national_tv/> {{cquote|I'm asking you, Kevin, for fuck's sake will you protect me just a small bit. For jaysus sake don't land me in it. I'm destroyed as it fucking is. … I can't bring out that 200 – that 250 – again. If that comes out again I'm fucking ruined, I'm bankrupt. … They can't find that 200. I never declared it.}}
{{cquote|Now, the 2500 – the 250 – that I gave you, I paid that directly. I never put that through my books or my account of anything, nobody's going to fucking get it, so I've got, you, know, I mean, I'm not even bringing that into it.}}
Journalist Michael Clifford, writing in the ''[[Irish Examiner]]'', drew comparisons between the response - or lack thereof - from the Irish government and the British government's past responses to tamer crimes such as [[Jeffrey Archer]]'s perjury and [[Chris Huhne]]'s perverting the course of justice. Clifford wrote that the Lowry scandal "tells us much about what passes for democracy in this State. [It] involves ''[[prima facie]]'' evidence that at least one crime may have been committed by serving TD and former government minister, Michael Lowry. In a proper democracy [...] this would be a matter for the police."<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Clifford|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/opinion/columnists/michael-clifford/lowry-and-inaction-of-gardarevenue-228210.html|title=Lowry and inaction of Garda/Revenue|newspaper=Irish Examiner|date=13 April 2013|accessdate=13 April 2013}}</ref>
The ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]'' published a transcript of the Lowry Tapes; however state broadcaster [[Raidió Teilifís Éireann|RTÉ]]'s coverage was roundly criticised and deemed inadequate. The ''Sunday Independent'' said RTÉ's self-censorship had become the story and ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' featured a piece captioned "Our state broadcaster must learn to confront, not cower."<ref>{{cite news|first=Eoghan|last=Harris|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/eoghan-harris/rtes-silence-over-lowry-tapes-is-now-the-story-29150350.html|title=RTÉ's silence over Lowry tapes is now the story|newspaper=Sunday Independent|date=24 March 2013|accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/rte-defends-coverage-of-the-lowry-tapes-851924-Mar2013/|title=RTÉ defends coverage of the ‘Lowry Tapes’|work=TheJournal.ie|date=31 March 2013|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref> One of the few mentions was provided by [[Marian Finucane]], one of RTÉ's highest earners, who brushed over the Lowry Tapes in two minutes at the end of her show when one of her panelists brought up the topic.<ref>{{cite news|first=Eilis|last=O'Hanlon|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/eilis-ohanlon-you-cant-find-time-to-discuss-lowry-the-public-begs-to-differ-29194820.html|title=You can't find time to discuss Lowry – the public begs to differ|newspaper=Sunday Independent|date=14 April 2013|accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref> ''[[Morning Ireland]]'' preferred to focus its political coverage on what were termed more trivial topics, such as [[Luke 'Ming' Flanagan]]'s driving technique and tweets by [[Gerry Adams]].<ref>{{cite news|first=John-Paul|last=McCarthy|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/johnpaul-mccarthy-montrose-fails-to-see-value-in-lowry-story-29135186.html|title=Montrose fails to see value in Lowry story: John-Paul McCarthy ponders the passive reaction of both the Government and RTÉ to the Lowry tapes|newspaper=Sunday Independent|date=17 March 2013|accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref>
On 14 March 2013, the Lowry Tapes were broadcast in full on national television, on the [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] programme ''[[Tonight with Vincent Browne]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jody|last=Corcoran|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/coalition-tension-over-lowry-tapes-29120885.html|title=Coalition tension over Lowry tapes|newspaper=Sunday Independent|date=10 March 2013|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=journal_conversation_aired_on_national_tv>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/michael-lowry-kevin-phelan-conversation-833051-Mar2013/|title=Gardaí examining Lowry tape as conversation is aired on national TV: Independent TD Michael Lowry can be heard making reference to a £250,000 payment which he said he never declared|work=TheJournal.ie|date=15 March 2013|accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref>
On 9 May 2013, [[Taoiseach]] [[Enda Kenny]] responded to "real concern" among the public over the Lowry Tapes but said he would not reopen the [[Moriarty Tribunal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2013/0509/391372-lowry-tapes/|title=Taoiseach rules out reopening Moriarty Tribunal over 'Lowry tapes'|work=RTÉ News|date=9 May 2013|accessdate=9 May 2013}}</ref>
