{{Infobox ancient site | name = Quelcatani | native_name = Qillqatani | alternate_name = Qelqatani | image = | alt = | caption = | map_type = Peru | map_alt = Qillqatani | map_caption = location in Peru | map_size = 240 | relief = 1 | coordinates = {{coord|16|56|58|S|69|53|22|W|display=inline,title}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://escholarship.org/uc/item/3ms9c4tb#page-2 |title=Exotic Goods, Chivay Obsidian, and Sociopolitical Change in the South-Central Andes (eScholarship) |publisher=Escholarship.org |date= |author= |accessdate= March 11, 2017}}</ref> | altitude_m = 4420 | altitude_ref = {{sfn|Peregrine|2001}} | location = [[Peru]], [[Puno Region]] | region = Lake Titicaca basin | type = | part_of = | length = | width = | area = {{convert|200|m2|sqft|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Peregrine|2001}} | height = | builder = | material = | built = c. 7500 BP | abandoned = 1472 AD{{sfn|Peregrine|2001}} | epochs = <!-- actually displays as "Periods" --> | cultures = | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations = | archaeologists = [[Mark Aldenderfer]] | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | notes = }} '''Qillqatani''' ([[Aymara language|Aymara]] ''qillqaña'' to write, ''-ta'' a [[suffix]] to indicate the [[participle]], ''-ni'' a suffix to indicate ownership, "the one with something written", Hispanicized ''Qelqatani, Quelcatani'') is an archaeological site in [[Peru]].<ref name=qillqatani>[http://mapaspects.org/tripcevich-phd-diss/ch3-archaeology-region-/34-chivay-obsidian-consump/342-qillqatani-rock-shelter mapaspects.org] "Qillqatani rock shelter"</ref> It is located above the [[Rio Chila]], in the [[Puno Region]], [[El Collao Province]], [[Santa Rosa District, El Collao|Santa Rosa District]], at a height of about {{convert|5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} above the riverbed.{{sfn|Peregrine|2001}} Qillqatani is surrounded by dry [[puna grassland|puna]].{{sfn|Peregrine|2001}}
The site was declared a National Cultural Heritage ''(Patrimonio Cultural)'' of Peru.<ref name=mincetur>[http://www.mincetur.gob.pe/TURISMO/OTROS/inventario%20turistico/Ficha.asp?cod_Ficha=3840 mincetur.gob.pe] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204051432/http://www.mincetur.gob.pe/TURISMO/OTROS/inventario%20turistico/Ficha.asp?cod_Ficha=3840 |date=February 4, 2014 }} "Arte rupestre de Qelqatani", retrieved on January 25, 2014</ref> Qillqatani is known for its elaborate rock art panels.
==Archaeology== Qillqatani is the first archaeological site in the [[Lake Titicaca]] basin to be systematically excavated. Archaeologists have identified 36 cultural strata at the site. From 7500 to 4000 [[Before present|BP]], Qillqatani was inhabited by hunter-gatherers as a seasonal campsite. These early occupants hunted mostly camelids, and some deer.{{sfn|Peregrine|2001}} From 3660 BP onwards, Qillqatani was inhabited by pastoralist camelid-herders who built houses and began to occupy the site long-term.{{sfn|Peregrine|2001}} These later occupants also began to trade with people from lower attitudes to obtain ''[[Chenopodium]]''.{{sfn|Peregrine|2001}}
