{{Other uses|Waffle (disambiguation)}}
'''Waffle''' is language without meaning; blathering, babbling, droning. One might waffle throughout an essay or a presentation, when not having enough material, or needing to fill in time. The term may be derived from the [[Scots language|Scots]] verb ''waff''<ref name=Safire2004/> "to wave, fluctuate".<ref>{{citation | author=[[John Jamieson]] | entry=WAFF | title=An etymological dictionary of the Scottish language | volume=2 | year=1808 | url=https://archive.org/details/etymologicaldict02jami}}</ref>

The term "to waffle", particularly in the [[United States|U.S.]], can also denote indecision about particular subjects; "waffling" can also mean changing one's mind frequently on a topic. ''Example: "Craig always waffles when he's speaking to Genevieve on the telephone". To which Genevieve usually replies "Come on Craig, come out with it!".'' In can be used as a derogatory term; to describe, for instance, a candidate or politician who is considered to easily switch sides on issues to curry political favor (i.e. "flip-flop"), as an [[waffle|easily flipped breakfast food with the same name]] – hence the waffle famously used to represent [[President of the United States|President]] [[Bill Clinton]] in the ''[[Doonesbury]]'' [[comic strip]].<ref name=Raum1994/>

