'''Ángel R. Cabada''' is a town ''([[settlement classification in Mexico#Veracruz|villa]])'' in the [[Mexican state]] of [[Veracruz]]. Located in the state's [[Papaloapan River]] region, it serves as the municipal seat for the [[Ángel R. Cabada (municipality)|surrounding municipality of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ángel R. Cabada, Veracruz|url=http://oc4jver.veracruz.gob.mx/Municipios/municipio?ciudad=30015 |publisher=Ministry of Finance and Planning, [[Veracruz|Government of State of Veracruz of Ignacio de la Llave]]|accessdate=4 September 2010|language=es}}</ref>
In the 2005 INEGI Census, the town reported a total population of 11,689.<ref name="EncicloMuni">{{cite web|title=Veracruz - Ángel R. Cabada|url=http://www.e-local.gob.mx/work/templates/enciclo/veracruz/municipios/30015a.htm |work=Enciclopedia de los Municipios de México|publisher=[[Instituto Nacional para el Federalismo y el Desarrollo Municipal]], Gobierno del Estado de Veracruz|accessdate=4 September 2010|language=es}}</ref>
The town is named after [[Ángel Rosario Cabada]] (1872-1921), an agrarian leader. Previously, the town was named El Mesón.<ref name="EncicloMuni" /> El Mesón had been a small regional center of the [[Olmec]] or [[Epi-Olmec culture]] during a period between 400 BCE and 100 CE. Local farmers found the El Mesón Stela in the 1950s. <ref>{{Cite web | last = Loughlin | first = Michael | title = Recorrido Arqueológico El Mesón | publisher = Foundation for the Advancement of Mesoamerican Studies, Inc. (FAMSI) | date = 2004 | url = http://www.famsi.org/cgi-bin/print_friendly.pl?file=02058 | format = HTML | doi = | accessdate = 4 September 2010}}</ref> ([[Tres Zapotes]], about 15 km south of El Mesón, was part of the [[Olmec heartland]].)
